in nature</a>, including the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyll=
otaxis" title=3D"Phyllotaxis">spiral arrangement of leaves</a> and other pa=
rts of vegetation.
</p><p>Some 20th-century <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artist" t=
itle=3D"Artist">artists</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ar=
chitect" title=3D"Architect">architects</a>, including <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Corbusier" title=3D"Le Corbusier">Le Corbusier</a> =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salvador_Dal%C3%AD" title=3D"S=
alvador Dal=C3=AD">Salvador Dal=C3=AD</a>, have proportioned their works to=
 approximate the golden ratio, believing it to be <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Aesthetics" title=3D"Aesthetics">aesthetically</a> pleasing=
. These uses often appear in the form of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Golden_rectangle" title=3D"Golden rectangle">golden rectangle</a>.
</p>
