n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number#History" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Fibonacci number">Fibonacci number =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></div>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mario_Livio" title=
=3D"Mario Livio">Mario Livio</a>,
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Some of the greatest mathematical mi=
nds of all ages, from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" =
title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title=3D"Ancient Greece">ancient Greece</a>, thr=
ough the medieval Italian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacci">Leonardo of Pisa</a> and the Renaissan=
ce astronomer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" tit=
le=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a>, to present-day scientific figur=
es such as Oxford physicist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_=
Penrose" title=3D"Roger Penrose">Roger Penrose</a>, have spent endless hour=
s over this simple ratio and its properties. ... Biologists, artists, music=
ians, historians, architects, psychologists, and even mystics have pondered=
 and debated the basis of its ubiquity and appeal. In fact, it is probably =
fair to say that the Golden Ratio has inspired thinkers of all disciplines =
like no other number in the history of mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOT=
NOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage6_6]_13-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cit=
e_note-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage6_=
6]-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p styl=
e=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8A<i>The Golden=
 Ratio: The Story of Phi, the World's Most Astonishing Number</i><span styl=
e=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title=3D"Ancien=
t Greece">Ancient Greek</a> mathematicians first studied the golden ratio b=
ecause of its frequent appearance in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELi=
vio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage4_4]_14-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage4_4]-14"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> the division of a line into "extreme and mean ratio" (the gold=
en section) is important in the geometry of regular <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagram#Geometry" title=3D"Pentagram">pentagrams</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagon" title=3D"Pentagon">pen=
tagons</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgold=
enratiostory00livipage7_7=E2=80=938]_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2002[https=
