<p>The golden ratio was studied peripherally over the next millennium. <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abu_Kamil" title=3D"Abu Kamil">Abu Kam=
il</a> (c. 850=E2=80=93930) employed it in his geometric calculations of pe=
ntagons and decagons; his writings influenced that of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci</a> (Leonardo =
of Pisa) (c. 1170=E2=80=931250), who used the ratio in related geometry pro=
blems but did not observe that it was connected to the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibon=
acci number">Fibonacci numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[ht=
tpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage88_88=E2=80=9396]_23-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage88_88=
%E2%80%9396]-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luca_Pacioli" title=3D"Luca=
 Pacioli">Luca Pacioli</a> named his book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Divina_proportione" title=3D"Divina proportione">Divina proporti=
one</a></i> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1509_in_literature" t=
itle=3D"1509 in literature">1509</a>) after the ratio; the book, largely pl=
agiarized from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piero_della_Frances=
ca" title=3D"Piero della Francesca">Piero della Francesca</a>, explored its=
 properties including its appearance in some of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solids" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Platonic =
solids">Platonic solids</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mackinnon_24-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-ma=
ckinnon-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveor=
gdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage131_131=E2=80=93132]_25-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTN=
OTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage131_131%E2%80%=
93132]-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_da=
_Vinci" title=3D"Leonardo da Vinci">Leonardo da Vinci</a>, who illustrated =
Pacioli's book, called the ratio the <i>sectio aurea</i> ('golden section')=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-baravalle_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-baravalle-26"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Tho=
ugh it is often said that Pacioli advocated the golden ratio's application =
to yield pleasing, harmonious proportions, Livio points out that the interp=
retation has been traced to an error in 1799, and that Pacioli actually adv=
ocated the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitruvius" title=3D"Vit=
ruvius">Vitruvian</a> system of rational proportions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FO=
OTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage134_134=E2=
=80=93135]_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenrat=
iostory00livipage134_134%E2%80%93135]-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Pacioli also saw Cath=
olic religious significance in the ratio, which led to his work's title. 16=
th-century mathematicians such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Rafael_Bombelli" title=3D"Rafael Bombelli">Rafael Bombelli</a> solved geome=
tric problems using the ratio.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsar=
chiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage141_141]_28-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTELi=
vio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage141_141]-28"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>
German mathematician Simon Jacob (d.&nbsp;1564) noted that <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#Relationship_to_Fibonacci_and_Lucas_n=
umbers">ratios of consecutive Fibonacci numbers converge to the golden rati=
o</a>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-schreiber_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-schreiber-29"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> this was rediscovered by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johanne=
s_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a> in 1608.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage=
151_151=E2=80=93152]_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
