"Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</a>. Kepler said of these:<link r=
el=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1244412=
712"></p><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Geometry has two great trea=
sures: one is the theorem of Pythagoras, the other the division of a line i=
nto extreme and mean ratio. The first we may compare to a mass of gold, the=
 second we may call a precious jewel.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fink_32-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-fink-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Eighteenth-century mathematicians <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Abraham_de_Moivre" title=3D"Abraham de Moivre">Abraham de Moivre</a>, <a=
