aus I Bernoulli">Nicolaus I Bernoulli</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> us=
ed a golden ratio-based formula which finds the value of a Fibonacci number=
 based on its placement in the sequence; in 1843, this was rediscovered by =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Philippe_Marie_Binet" titl=
e=3D"Jacques Philippe Marie Binet">Jacques Philippe Marie Binet</a>, for wh=
om it was named "Binet's formula".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-beutelspacher_petri_3=
3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ra=
tio#cite_note-beutelspacher_petri-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Ohm" title=3D"Martin Ohm">Martin Ohm</a> first used =
the German term <i>goldener Schnitt</i> ('golden section') to describe the =
ratio in 1835.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerz-Fischler1998167=E2=80=93170_=
34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_r=
atio#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerz-Fischler1998167%E2%80%93170-34"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Sully" title=3D"James Sully">Ja=
mes Sully</a> used the equivalent English term in 1875.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
FOOTNOTEPosamentierLehmann20118_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPosamentierLehmann20=
118-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>By 1910, inventor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Barr=
