" title=3D"Zome">Zometoy</a> model.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zome" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Zome">zome</a> construction system, developed by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Baer" title=3D"Steve Baer">Steve Baer</a> in=
 the late 1960s, is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
cosahedral_symmetry" title=3D"Icosahedral symmetry">symmetry system</a> of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedron" title=3D"Icosahed=
ron">icosahedron</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodecahedron"=
 title=3D"Dodecahedron">dodecahedron</a>, and uses the golden ratio ubiquit=
ously. Between 1973 and 1974, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roge=
r_Penrose" title=3D"Roger Penrose">Roger Penrose</a> developed <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penrose_tiling" title=3D"Penrose tiling">Penro=
se tiling</a>, a pattern related to the golden ratio both in the ratio of a=
reas of its two rhombic tiles and in their relative frequency within the pa=
ttern.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gardner_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-gardner-41"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
is gained in interest after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Sh=
echtman" title=3D"Dan Shechtman">Dan Shechtman</a>'s Nobel-winning 1982 dis=
covery of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasicrystal" title=3D"Q=
uasicrystal">quasicrystals</a> with icosahedral symmetry, which were soon a=
fterwards explained through analogies to the Penrose tiling.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-quasicrystals_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-quasicrystals-42"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
