y</h3></div>
<p>The golden ratio is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irration=
al_number" title=3D"Irrational number">irrational number</a>. Below are two=
 short proofs of irrationality:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Contradiction_from_an_expre=
ssion_in_lowest_terms">Contradiction from an expression in lowest terms</h4=
></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Whirling_squares.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/2/22/Whirling_squares.svg/250px-Whirling_squares.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"158" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"915" data-file-height=3D"579"></a><figcaption>If <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span> were <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D"Rational number=
">rational</a>, then it would be the ratio of sides of a rectangle with int=
eger sides (the rectangle comprising the entire diagram). But it would also=
 be a ratio of integer sides of the smaller rectangle (the rightmost portio=
n of the diagram) obtained by deleting a square. The sequence of decreasing=
 integer side lengths formed by deleting squares cannot be continued indefi=
nitely because the positive integers have a lower bound, so <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span> cannot be rational=
.</figcaption></figure>
<p>This is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_by_infinite_des=
cent" title=3D"Proof by infinite descent">proof by infinite descent</a>. Re=
call that:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
996643573"><div class=3D"block-indent" style=3D"padding-left: 1.6em;">the w=
hole is the longer part plus the shorter part;<br>
the whole is to the longer part as the longer part is to the shorter part.<=
/div>
