</p><p>Both the Fibonacci sequence and the sequence of Lucas numbers can be=
 used to generate approximate forms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Golden_spiral" title=3D"Golden spiral">golden spiral</a> (which is=
 a special form of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_s=
piral" title=3D"Logarithmic spiral">logarithmic spiral</a>) using quarter-c=
ircles with radii from these sequences, differing only slightly from the <i=
>true</i> golden logarithmic spiral. <i>Fibonacci spiral</i> is generally t=
he term used for spirals that approximate golden spirals using Fibonacci nu=
mber-sequenced squares and quarter-circles.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometry">Geometry</h3></di=
v>
<p>The golden ratio features prominently in geometry. For example, it is in=
trinsically involved in the internal symmetry of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagon" title=3D"Pentagon">pentagon</a>, and extends t=
o form part of the coordinates of the vertices of a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#Cartesian_coordinates" title=3D"Regu=
lar dodecahedron">regular dodecahedron</a>, as well as those of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron" title=3D"Regular ico=
sahedron">regular icosahedron</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BurgerStarbird_52-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#c=
ite_note-BurgerStarbird-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It features in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler_triangle" title=3D"Kepler triangle">Kepler =
triangle</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penrose_tilings" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Penrose tilings">Penrose tilings</a> too, as=
 well as in various other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polytope=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polytopes">polytopes</a>.
</p>
