ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cit=
e_note-loeb-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The pentagon can thus be subdivided into two go=
lden gnomons and a central golden triangle. The five points of a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagram" title=3D"Pentagram">regular penta=
gram</a> are golden triangles,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-loeb_55-2" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-loeb-=
55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> as are the ten triangles formed by connecting the vertices =
of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_decagon" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Regular decagon">regular decagon</a> to its center point=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-miller_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-miller-56"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Bisecting one of the base angles of the golden triangle subdivides i=
t into a smaller golden triangle and a golden gnomon. Analogously, any acut=
e isosceles triangle can be subdivided into a similar triangle and an obtus=
e isosceles triangle, but the golden triangle is the only one for which thi=
s subdivision is made by the angle bisector, because it is the only isoscel=
es triangle whose base angle is twice its apex angle. The angle bisector of=
 the golden triangle subdivides the side that it meets in the golden ratio,=
 and the areas of the two subdivided pieces are also in the golden ratio.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-loeb_55-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-loeb-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If the apex angle of the golden gnomon is <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Angle_trisection" title=3D"Angle trisection">trisected</a>, =
the trisector again subdivides it into a smaller golden gnomon and a golden=
 triangle. The trisector subdivides the base in the golden ratio, and the t=
wo pieces have areas in the golden ratio. Analogously, any obtuse triangle =
can be subdivided into a similar triangle and an acute isosceles triangle, =
but the golden gnomon is the only one for which this subdivision is made by=
 the angle trisector, because it is the only isosceles triangle whose apex =
angle is three times its base angle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-loeb_55-4" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note=
-loeb-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading5"><h5 id=3D"Penrose_tilings">Penrose ti=
lings</h5></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penrose_tiling" titl=
e=3D"Penrose tiling">Penrose tiling</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kite_Dart.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description">=
<img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Kite_=
Dart.svg/250px-Kite_Dart.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"156" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"225" data-file-height=
=3D"140"></a><figcaption>The kite and dart tiles of the Penrose tiling. The=
 colored arcs divide each edge in the golden ratio; when two tiles share an=
 edge, their arcs must match.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The golden ratio appears prominently in the <i>Penrose tiling</i>, a fam=
ily of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aperiodic_tiling" title=3D"=
Aperiodic tiling">aperiodic tilings</a> of the plane developed by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Penrose" title=3D"Roger Penrose">Ro=
ger Penrose</a>, inspired by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johan=
nes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a>'s remark that pen=
tagrams, decagons, and other shapes could fill gaps that pentagonal shapes =
alone leave when tiled together.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tilings_and_Patterns_57=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rat=
io#cite_note-Tilings_and_Patterns-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Several variations of thi=
s tiling have been studied, all of whose prototiles exhibit the golden rati=
o:
</p>
<ul><li>Penrose's original version of this tiling used four shapes: regular=
 pentagons and pentagrams, "boat" figures with three points of a pentagram,=
 and "diamond" shaped rhombi.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pentaplexity_58-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-pentaplexity-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The kite and dart Penrose tiling uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kite_(geometry)" title=3D"Kite (geometry)">kites</a> with three int=
erior angles of <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-ele=
ment mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-mat=
h-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/19=
