<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_spirals" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Logarithmic spirals">Logarithmic spirals</a> are <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-similar" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Self-similar">self-similar</a> spirals where distances covered per tu=
rn are in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_progression" t=
itle=3D"Geometric progression">geometric progression</a>. A logarithmic spi=
ral whose radius increases by a factor of the golden ratio for each quarter=
-turn is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_spiral"=
 title=3D"Golden spiral">golden spiral</a>. These spirals can be approximat=
ed by quarter-circles that grow by the golden ratio,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-qua=
rter-circles_69-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-quarter-circles-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or their approx=
imations generated from Fibonacci numbers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-diedrichs_70-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rati=
o#cite_note-diedrichs-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> often depicted inscribed within a spi=
raling pattern of squares growing in the same ratio. The exact logarithmic =
spiral form of the golden spiral can be described by the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system" title=3D"Polar coordinate s=
ystem">polar equation</a> with <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathm=
l-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http=
