<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Architecture">Architecture<=
/h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_a=
nd_architecture" title=3D"Mathematics and architecture">Mathematics and arc=
hitecture</a></div>
<p>The Swiss <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architect" title=3D"A=
rchitect">architect</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Corbusi=
er" title=3D"Le Corbusier">Le Corbusier</a>, famous for his contributions t=
o the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modernism" title=3D"Modernis=
m">modern</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Style_=
(architecture)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Style (archite=
cture)">international style</a>, centered his design philosophy on systems =
of harmony and proportion. Le Corbusier's faith in the mathematical order o=
f the universe was closely bound to the golden ratio and the Fibonacci seri=
es, which he described as "rhythms apparent to the eye and clear in their r=
elations with one another. And these rhythms are at the very root of human =
activities. They resound in man by an organic inevitability, the same fine =
inevitability which causes the tracing out of the Golden Section by childre=
n, old men, savages and the learned."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-modulor_80-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_=
note-modulor-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Frings_81-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-Fring=
s-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Le Corbusier explicitly used the golden ratio in his <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulor" title=3D"Modulor">Modulor</a> system for=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scale_(ratio)" title=3D"Scale=
 (ratio)">scale</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proportion_=
(architecture)" title=3D"Proportion (architecture)">architectural proportio=
n</a>. He saw this system as a continuation of the long tradition of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitruvius" title=3D"Vitruvius">Vitruvius=
</a>, Leonardo da Vinci's "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitruvi=
an_Man" title=3D"Vitruvian Man">Vitruvian Man</a>", the work of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_Battista_Alberti" title=3D"Leon Battista=
 Alberti">Leon Battista Alberti</a>, and others who used the proportions of=
 the human body to improve the appearance and function of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architecture" title=3D"Architecture">architecture</=
a>.
</p><p>In addition to the golden ratio, Le Corbusier based the system on <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthropometry" title=3D"Anthropometr=
y">human measurements</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonac=
ci_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibonacci numbers">Fibonacci num=
bers</a>, and the double unit. He took suggestion of the golden ratio in hu=
man proportions to an extreme: he sectioned his model human body's height a=
t the navel with the two sections in golden ratio, then subdivided those se=
ctions in golden ratio at the knees and throat; he used these golden ratio =
proportions in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulor" title=
=3D"Modulor">Modulor</a> system. Le Corbusier's 1927 <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Villa_Stein" title=3D"Villa Stein">Villa Stein</a> in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garches" title=3D"Garches">Garches</=
a> exemplified the Modulor system's application. The villa's rectangular gr=
ound plan, elevation, and inner structure closely approximate golden rectan=
gles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-modulor2_82-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-modulor2-82"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another Swiss architect, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
rio_Botta" title=3D"Mario Botta">Mario Botta</a>, bases many of his designs=
 on geometric figures. Several private houses he designed in Switzerland ar=
e composed of squares and circles, cubes and cylinders. In a house he desig=
ned in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origlio" title=3D"Origlio">=
Origlio</a>, the golden ratio is the proportion between the central section=
 and the side sections of the house.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-urwin_83-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-urwin-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
