<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Music">Music</h3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ern%C5%91_Lendvai" title=3D"Ern=
=C5=91 Lendvai">Ern=C5=91 Lendvai</a> analyzes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9la_Bart%C3%B3k" title=3D"B=C3=A9la Bart=C3=B3k">B=C3=A9=
la Bart=C3=B3k</a>'s works as being based on two opposing systems, that of =
the golden ratio and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acoustic_=
scale" title=3D"Acoustic scale">acoustic scale</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-lend=
vai_95-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold=
en_ratio#cite_note-lendvai-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> though other music scholars reje=
ct that analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetai=
lsgoldenratiostory00livipage190_190]_96-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2002[https=
archiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage190_190]-96"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> French =
composer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erik_Satie" title=3D"Erik=
 Satie">Erik Satie</a> used the golden ratio in several of his pieces, incl=
uding <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonneries_de_la_Rose%2BCr=
oix" title=3D"Sonneries de la Rose+Croix">Sonneries de la Rose+Croix</a></i=
>. The golden ratio is also apparent in the organization of the sections in=
 the music of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debussy" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Debussy">Debussy</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Reflets_dans_l%27eau" title=3D"Reflets dans l'eau">Reflets dans=
 l'eau</a> (Reflections in water)</i>, from <i>Images</i> (1st series, 1905=
), in which "the sequence of keys is marked out by the intervals <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">34,</span> <span class=3D"texhtml">21,</span> <span class=3D"=
texhtml">13</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">8,</span> and the main clima=
x sits at the phi position".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Smith_97-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-Smith-=
97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The musicologist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roy_Howat"=
 title=3D"Roy Howat">Roy Howat</a> has observed that the formal boundaries =
of Debussy's <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Mer_(Debussy)" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"La Mer (Debussy)">La Mer</a></i> correspond =
exactly to the golden section.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-howat_98-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-howa=
t-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Trezise finds the intrinsic evidence "remarkable", but ca=
utions that no written or reported evidence suggests that Debussy conscious=
ly sought such proportions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-trezise_99-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-trezi=
se-99"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Music theorists including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
ans_Zender" title=3D"Hans Zender">Hans Zender</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heinz_Bohlen" title=3D"Heinz Bohlen">Heinz Bohlen</a> h=
ave experimented with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/833_cent=
s_scale" title=3D"833 cents scale">833 cents scale</a>, a musical scale bas=
ed on using the golden ratio as its fundamental <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Musical_interval" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Musical inte=
rval">musical interval</a>. When measured in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cent_(music)" title=3D"Cent (music)">cents</a>, a logarithmic sc=
ale for musical intervals, the golden ratio is approximately 833.09 cents.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-833cents_100-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-833cents-100"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Nature">Nature</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Aeonium_tabuliforme.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
4/4f/Aeonium_tabuliforme.jpg/250px-Aeonium_tabuliforme.jpg" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"190" height=3D"274" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"1800" data-file-height=3D"2592"></a><figcaption>Detail of the saucer pl=
ant, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeonium_tabuliforme" title=
=3D"Aeonium tabuliforme">Aeonium tabuliforme</a></i>, showing the multiple =
spiral arrangement (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parastichy" ti=
tle=3D"Parastichy">parastichy</a>)</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patterns_in_nature" =
title=3D"Patterns in nature">Patterns in nature</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number#Nature"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibonacci number">Fibonacci number =C2=A7&n=
bsp;Nature</a></div>
<p>Johannes Kepler wrote that "the image of man and woman stems from the di=
vine proportion. In my opinion, the propagation of plants and the progeniti=
ve acts of animals are in the same ratio".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio=
2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage154_154]_101-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage154_1=
54]-101"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The psychologist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolf_Zeis=
ing" title=3D"Adolf Zeising">Adolf Zeising</a> noted that the golden ratio =
appeared in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllotaxis" title=3D"=
Phyllotaxis">phyllotaxis</a> and argued from these <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Patterns_in_nature" title=3D"Patterns in nature">patterns =
in nature</a> that the golden ratio was a universal law.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-padovan_102-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Golden_ratio#cite_note-padovan-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Zeising wrote in 1854 of =
a universal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogenesis" title=3D=
"Orthogenesis">orthogenetic</a> law of "striving for beauty and completenes=
s in the realms of both nature and art".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-zeising_103-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#c=
ite_note-zeising-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>However, some have argued that many apparent manifestations of the g=
olden ratio in nature, especially in regard to animal dimensions, are ficti=
tious.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pommersheim_104-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-pommersheim-104"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
