<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Optimization">Optimization<=
/h3></div>
<p>There is no known general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algor=
ithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> to arrange a given number of nodes =
evenly on a sphere, for any of several definitions of even distribution (se=
e, for example, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomson_problem=
" title=3D"Thomson problem">Thomson problem</a></i> or <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tammes_problem" title=3D"Tammes problem">Tammes pro=
blem</a></i>). However, a useful approximation results from dividing the sp=
here into parallel bands of equal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Surface_area" title=3D"Surface area">surface area</a> and placing one node =
in each band at longitudes spaced by a golden section of the circle, i.e. <=
span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
lttext=3D"{\displaystyle 360^{\circ }~\!/\varphi \approx 222.5^{\circ }\!}"=
>
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
