<p>The golden ratio is a critical element to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Golden-section_search" title=3D"Golden-section search">golden-se=
ction search</a> as well.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Disputed_observations">Disp=
uted observations</h2></div>
<p>Examples of disputed observations of the golden ratio include the follow=
ing:
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/0/08/NautilusCutawayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg/250px-NautilusCuta=
wayLogarithmicSpiral.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"189" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2240" data-file-height=3D"1693"=
></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautilus" title=
=3D"Nautilus">Nautilus</a> shells are often erroneously claimed to be golde=
n-proportioned.</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>Specific proportions in the bodies of vertebrates (including humans=
) are often claimed to be in the golden ratio; for example the ratio of suc=
cessive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phalanx_bone" title=3D"Pha=
lanx bone">phalangeal</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meta=
carpal_bones" title=3D"Metacarpal bones">metacarpal bones</a> (finger bones=
) has been said to approximate the golden ratio. There is a large variation=
 in the real measures of these elements in specific individuals, however, a=
nd the proportion in question is often significantly different from the gol=
den ratio.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pheasant_107-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-pheasant-107"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-vanLaack_108-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-vanLaack-108"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup></li>
<li>The shells of mollusks such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Nautilus" title=3D"Nautilus">nautilus</a> are often claimed to be in t=
he golden ratio.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dunlap_109-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-dunlap-109"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The growth of nautilus shells follows a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_spiral" title=3D"Logarithmic spiral">logarithmic=
 spiral</a>, and it is sometimes erroneously claimed that any logarithmic s=
piral is related to the golden ratio,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-falbo_110-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_n=
ote-falbo-110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> or sometimes claimed that each new chamber is g=
olden-proportioned relative to the previous one.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-moscovi=
ch_111-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold=
en_ratio#cite_note-moscovich-111"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>105<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, measurements of nau=
tilus shells do not support this claim.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-shellspirals_112=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rat=
io#cite_note-shellspirals-112"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>106<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Historian <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Man_(author)" t=
itle=3D"John Man (author)">John Man</a> states that both the pages and text=
 area of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gutenberg_Bible" titl=
e=3D"Gutenberg Bible">Gutenberg Bible</a> were "based on the golden section=
 shape". However, according to his own measurements, the ratio of height to=
 width of the pages is <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 1.45}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1.45</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1.45}</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/6fd59f65790a82a7e93d98320402fdfd87d86622" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:4.134ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1.4=
5}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gutenberg_113-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-g=
utenberg-113"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Studies by psychologists, starting with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Gustav_Fechner" title=3D"Gustav Fechner">Gustav Fechner</a> <abbr=
 title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891876=
</span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Fechner_114-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-Fechner-114"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> have been devised to test the idea that the golden ratio plays a role in=
 human perception of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beauty" title=
=3D"Beauty">beauty</a>. While Fechner found a preference for rectangle rati=
os centered on the golden ratio, later attempts to carefully test such a hy=
pothesis have been, at best, inconclusive.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio=
2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage7_7]_115-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-F=
OOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage7_7]-115">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>109<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-livio_plus_84-2" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-livio_plus-84"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup></li>
<li>In investing, some practitioners of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Technical_analysis" title=3D"Technical analysis">technical analysis</=
a> use the golden ratio to indicate support of a price level, or resistance=
 to price increases, of a stock or commodity; after significant price chang=
es up or down, new support and resistance levels are supposedly found at or=
 near prices related to the starting price via the golden ratio.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-osler_116-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-osler-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>110<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The use of the golde=
n ratio in investing is also related to more complicated patterns described=
 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_numbers" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Fibonacci numbers">Fibonacci numbers</a> (e.g. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliott_wave_principle" title=3D"Elliott =
wave principle">Elliott wave principle</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_retracement" title=3D"Fibonacci retracement">Fibonac=
ci retracement</a>). However, other market analysts have published analyses=
 suggesting that these percentages and patterns are not supported by the da=
ta.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-magicdow_117-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-magicdow-117"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Egyptian_pyramids">Egyptian=
 pyramids</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Egypt._Pyramids._Pyramids_and_palm_grove_refl=
ections_LOC_matpc.23063.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"http=
s://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Egypt._Pyramids._Pyra=
mids_and_palm_grove_reflections_LOC_matpc.23063.jpg/250px-Egypt._Pyramids._=
Pyramids_and_palm_grove_reflections_LOC_matpc.23063.jpg" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"177" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
4811" data-file-height=3D"3405"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Pyramid_of_Giza" title=3D"Great Pyramid of Giza">Gr=
eat Pyramid of Giza</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Pyramid_of_Giza" titl=
e=3D"Great Pyramid of Giza">Great Pyramid of Giza</a> (also known as the Py=
ramid of Cheops or Khufu) has been analyzed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Pyramidology" title=3D"Pyramidology">pyramidologists</a> as ha=
ving a doubled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler_triangle" ti=
tle=3D"Kepler triangle">Kepler triangle</a> as its cross-section. If this t=
heory were true, the golden ratio would describe the ratio of distances fro=
m the midpoint of one of the sides of the pyramid to its apex, and from the=
 same midpoint to the center of the pyramid's base. However, imprecision in=
 measurement caused in part by the removal of the outer surface of the pyra=
mid makes it impossible to distinguish this theory from other numerical the=
ories of the proportions of the pyramid, based on <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pi" title=3D"Pi">pi</a> or on whole-number ratios. The cons=
ensus of modern scholars is that this pyramid's proportions are not based o=
n the golden ratio, because such a basis would be inconsistent both with wh=
at is known about Egyptian mathematics from the time of construction of the=
 pyramid, and with Egyptian theories of architecture and proportion used in=
 their other works.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-greatpyramid_118-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-greatpy=
ramid-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>112<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"The_Parthenon">The Partheno=
n</h3></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:The_Parthenon_in_Athens.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/The_Parthenon_in_=
Athens.jpg/330px-The_Parthenon_in_Athens.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
80" height=3D"197" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1144" data-=
file-height=3D"804"></a><figcaption>Many of the proportions of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parthenon" title=3D"Parthenon">Parthenon<=
/a> are alleged to exhibit the golden ratio, but this has largely been disc=
redited.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdetailsgoldenr=
atiostory00livipage74_74=E2=80=9375]_119-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2002[http=
sarchiveorgdetailsgoldenratiostory00livipage74_74%E2%80%9375]-119"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>113<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parthenon" title=3D"Parthen=
on">Parthenon</a>'s fa=C3=A7ade (c. 432 BC) as well as elements of its fa=
=C3=A7ade and elsewhere are said by some to be circumscribed by golden rect=
angles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Polemic_120-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-Polemic-120"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Other scholars deny that the Greeks had any aesthetic association with go=
lden ratio. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Dev=
lin" title=3D"Keith Devlin">Keith Devlin</a> says, "Certainly, the oft repe=
ated assertion that the Parthenon in Athens is based on the golden ratio is=
 not supported by actual measurements. In fact, the entire story about the =
Greeks and golden ratio seems to be without foundation."<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-mathinstinct_121-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-mathinstinct-121"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>115<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midhat_J._Gazal%C3%A9" title=3D"Midhat J. Gazal=
=C3=A9">Midhat J. Gazal=C3=A9</a> affirms that "It was not until Euclid ...=
 that the golden ratio's mathematical properties were studied."<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-gazal=C3=A9_122-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-gazal%C3%A9-122"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>From measurements of 15 temples, 18 monumental tombs, 8 sarcophagi, =
and 58 grave stelae from the fifth century BC to the second century AD, one=
 researcher concluded that the golden ratio was totally absent from Greek a=
rchitecture of the classical fifth century BC, and almost absent during the=
 following six centuries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-foutakis_123-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-fouta=
kis-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
Later sources like Vitruvius (first century&nbsp;BC) exclusively discuss pr=
oportions that can be expressed in whole numbers, i.e. commensurate as oppo=
sed to irrational proportions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modern_art">Modern art</h3>=
</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Albert_Gleizes,_1912,_Les_Baigneuses,_oil_on_=
canvas,_105_x_171_cm,_Paris,_Mus%C3%A9e_d%27Art_Moderne_de_la_Ville_de_Pari=
s.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.o=
rg/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Albert_Gleizes%2C_1912%2C_Les_Baigneuses%2C=
_oil_on_canvas%2C_105_x_171_cm%2C_Paris%2C_Mus%C3%A9e_d%27Art_Moderne_de_la=
_Ville_de_Paris.jpg/250px-Albert_Gleizes%2C_1912%2C_Les_Baigneuses%2C_oil_o=
n_canvas%2C_105_x_171_cm%2C_Paris%2C_Mus%C3%A9e_d%27Art_Moderne_de_la_Ville=
_de_Paris.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"155" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"2056" data-file-height=3D"1277"></a><figca=
ption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Gleizes" title=3D"Alb=
ert Gleizes">Albert Gleizes</a>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Les_Baigneuses_(Gleizes)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Les Baigneuses (=
Gleizes)">Les Baigneuses</a></i> (1912)</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Section_d%27Or" title=3D"Se=
ction d'Or">Section d'Or</a> ('Golden Section') was a collective of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Painting" title=3D"Painting">painters</a>=
, sculptors, poets and critics associated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cubism" title=3D"Cubism">Cubism</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Orphism_(art)" title=3D"Orphism (art)">Orphism</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-centrepompidou1_124-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-centrepompidou1-124"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Active from 1911 to around 1914, they adopted the name both to highli=
ght that Cubism represented the continuation of a grand tradition, rather t=
han being an isolated movement, and in homage to the mathematical harmony a=
ssociated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georges_Seurat" tit=
le=3D"Georges Seurat">Georges Seurat</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-centrepompidou=
2_125-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golde=
n_ratio#cite_note-centrepompidou2-125"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>119<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (Several authors have c=
laimed that Seurat employed the golden ratio in his paintings, but Seurat's=
 writings and paintings suggest that he employed simple whole-number ratios=
 and any approximation of the golden ratio was coincidental.)<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-seuratclaims_126-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-seuratclaims-126"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Cubis=
ts observed in its harmonies, geometric structuring of motion and form, "th=
e primacy of idea over nature", "an absolute scientific clarity of concepti=
on".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-herbert_127-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio#cite_note-herbert-127"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> H=
owever, despite this general interest in mathematical harmony, whether the =
paintings featured in the celebrated 1912 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Section_d%27Or#Salon_de_la_Section_d'Or,_1912" title=3D"Section d'O=
r"><i>Salon de la Section d'Or</i></a> exhibition used the golden ratio in =
any compositions is more difficult to determine. Livio, for example, claims=
 that they did not,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2002[httpsarchiveorgdet=
ailsgoldenratiostory00livipage169_169]_128-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
